# Go Standards

- Prefer interfaces for external dependencies (HTTP clients, DB, queues). Inject in constructors.
- Use `context.Context` as first parameter for cancellation and timeouts.
- Write table-driven tests for business logic; one test function per behavior, cases in a slice.
- Break functions; keep them small and single-purpose.
- No comments for obvious logic; short comments only for non-obvious or spec-critical behavior.
- Preserve existing patterns in the codebase when adding code.

## Table-driven test shape

```go
func TestParsePrefs(t *testing.T) {
	tests := []struct {
		name    string
		input   string
		want    Preference
		wantErr bool
	}{
		{"ok", `{"email":true}`, Preference{Email: true}, false},
		{"invalid", `{`, Preference{}, true},
	}
	for _, tt := range tests {
		t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {
			got, err := ParsePrefs(tt.input)
			if (err != nil) != tt.wantErr {
				t.Fatalf("err = %v, wantErr %v", err, tt.wantErr)
			}
			if !reflect.DeepEqual(got, tt.want) {
				t.Errorf("got %+v, want %+v", got, tt.want)
			}
		})
	}
}
```

## Error handling

- Return errors; do not swallow. Wrap with `fmt.Errorf("…: %w", err)` when adding context.
- For retries/backoff, use explicit intervals (e.g. from spec: 1 min, 5 min, 15 min).
